			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2010</a> paper:</span><br><i>Evaluating a Textual Feature Modelling Language: Four Industrial Case Studies</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ArnaudHubaux.html">Arnaud Hubaux</a>, <a href="../profile/QuentinBoucher.html">Quentin Boucher</a>, <a href="../profile/HermanHartmann.html">Herman Hartmann</a>, <a href="../profile/RaphaëlMichel.html">Raphaël Michel</a>, <a href="../profile/PatrickHeymans.html">Patrick Heymans</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_23">10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_23</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The primary contribution is an evaluation via multiple industrial case studies of a textual feature-modeling language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagL">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> The language under evaluation is for feature modeling and variability management.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL">T6B: Industrial</span></a><ul><li> The evidence base comes from industrial case studies rather than purely academic examples.
</li></ul></li></ul>
